Highway of Emotions
You're the Boss

A state of well-being in which the individual realizes his or her own abilities, is able to appropriately express all emotions, can cope with the normal stresses of life, can work productively and fruitfully, and is able to make a contribution to his or her community.

The highway of emotions is sometimes a tough one to drive down and quite challenging for many people. Emotional health and well-being involves a lot and is always a work in progress. Having strong emotional wellness can lead to less stress, more happiness, and even add years onto your life! This is definitely something to focus and spend time on. Emotional wellness is not simply one factor or a single emotion, it involves how you manage your emotions and behaviors (both negative and positive), cope with stress, adapt to change, amongst many other things. Identify what your strengths are and explore your need areas.

You’re the boss, if emotional well-being is what you want, it is what you shall receive. Possessing a strong emotional well-being is shown to have positive affects on job happiness, developing meaningful relationships, and even your physical health. You are doing a solid job maintaining good emotional health. Given this, still explore new goals, different ways to express your emotions, and building new connections in life.
Emotional Well-Being
When grading this factor focus on the number of hobbies you have and the amount of pleasure you get from engaging in them. Remember, this doesn’t mean there is a “magical number” of hobbies to have.

“The art of being happy lies in the power of extracting happiness from common things.” ~ Henry Ward Beecher Sometimes in order to remain interested, an individual is required to extract something interesting out of what you typically find common. Take a look at your life, your hobbies, your job, your friends and extract something unique about each of them. Maybe you already have something in your life you can build an interest around or start something new. Speaking to friends and family can help stir up useful ideas for new hobbies or perspectives to build on.

“The art of being happy lies in the power of extracting happiness from common things.” ~ Henry Ward Beecher Having interests and hobbies adds significant value to life as you may know by now. Continue to pursue things that interest you and don’t be afraid to try something new. An individual’s interest can increase even after starting a new hobby.
Hobbies & Interests

For this factor focus on the number of genuine and intimate relationships you have in your life. These relationships may include really close friends, significant others, or family members. Remember this is not how many “friends” you have, it is how many deep and/or intimate
relationships you have.

Real life for most people does not look like The Notebook or Sex In The City. There are many reasons why we come up short in these areas, and maybe you already know why. Previous painful baggage, fear of rejection, lack of experience, anxieties, could all add to the challenge of developing these relationships. Start by looking at the strongest relationships you actually do have and examine how you connect with those people. Is it through vulnerability and honesty, similarities, being physically close, or shared experiences?

You got this down! Having connection and love in our lives is a very important human need. Many people shy away from intimate and deep relationships because of our fear of “rejection” and “not being good enough”. You have allowed yourself to at least get a taste of what kind of value these relationships can bring to your life. Keep it up and continue building new relationships.
Genuine, Intimate, and Deep Relationships

Social support and networks are typically made up of family, friends, and peers. They bring a sense of belonging, safety, security, and increased self-worth. Grade the depth and quality of your social support and networks.

By any chance do you live in your parent’s basement? In all seriousness many people feel the need to turn inward during a time of need. Research shows that social support and networks (not Facebook or Twitter!) not only increase your happiness, but improve your odds of being successful with goals. Not to mention it reduces anxiety! It is not too late to start. Ask yourself what type of support you need and find individuals that are capable of providing it. The detective work starts now!

Nice going president popular, you got it going on! While many feel the need to turn inward during times of need you have a reliable social support network to help you. Research shows that social support and networks (not Facebook or Twitter!) not only increase your happiness, but the odds of fulfilling your goals. Keep using and building your support circles to greater success.
Social Support & Social Networks

Physical Health for our use will include five areas of focus. Those areas include participating in regular physical activity, maintaining good nutrition, receiving adequate rest/sleep, being up-to-date with medical self care, and low use of alcohol and drugs.

Look good, feel good. Either you have new changes you are putting into practice or you have this health thing down. As you probably know by now, your physical health impacts a lot of other aspect of your life such as your mood, weight, sleep, appetite, and energy. Keep eating well and participating in a variety of exercises to reap the benefits of good physical health.

I am not here to tell you that you need to exercise more. Sure, that might be part of it but there is more to it. Start by asking yourself, is my physical health a problem? If you answered “no”, improving your physical health isn’t on your radar quite yet. If you do see there to be an issue educate yourself, find support, make a commitment, and set some goals. Your physical health has massive impacts on your energy, sleep, motivation, weight, and mood.
Physical Health

This is one of the most important factors to fulfillment. Contributing doesn’t necessarily mean donating money, it also means donating time, skills, efforts, and much more. This factor involves grading the extent to which you give back outside of yourself.

Okay, maybe finding ways to give back and contribute is a little more tough then originally planned. Studies show contributing outside of yourself and giving back is a major contributor to an individual’s fulfillment. Things like time, motivation, availability, or even ideas on how to contribute could be the culprits that are holding you back. Start small, simple, and manageable. Do your detective work and find out what factors are holding you back, find new creative ways to contribute, and experience the rush of fulfillment in no time.

Congratulations! You have found a way to contribute meaningfully. Maybe you volunteer, donate, spend time with individuals that value your company, or even go the (sometimes unrecognized) extra mile at work “just because you want to”. Studies show that giving back outside of yourself is a significant contributor to an individual’s personal fulfillment, so continue finding ways to volunteer, help out other individuals, and give back to your community.
Contribution & Giving Back

It is quite hard to maintain motivation and fulfillment when you don’t enjoy what you are doing! This factor is graded based on how interested, involved, motivated, and challenged you are at work and play.

Ooo look at that airplane, oh sorry what did you say? Keeping busy and focused may not come naturally but it doesn’t mean you can’t make simple changes to improve this area of your life. Being engaged at work and play doesn’t mean you have to absolutely love what you are doing ALL of the time. It simply means you must start finding meaning and value in what you are doing during that time.

Mission not impossible! It looks like you have no problem staying engaged and focused with your time! You and I both know that downtime can be relaxing or down right boring! Continue keeping busy at work and play with a variety of things that sometimes challenge you and occasionally relax you. Remember to take breaks and keep that momentum going.
Being Engaged at Work & at Play

Job Happiness and Satisfaction relies on a couple factors. First, you should focus on the extent of which your goals, expectations, and desires are being met by your job. Second, think about what level of fulfillment, growth, and motivation does your work environment, peers, and responsibilities provide to you.

So your job’s a chore, you may not get payed enough, and you love the sound of your next vacation day. Sound about right? Well if only it was that easy to jump ship and get your dream job. While you at your current job, trying “re-writing the job description” and changing your perspective regarding the impact you are having and the value you bring. While your perspective is shifting, get involved in understanding what you “enjoy” doing and not simply what you are “good” at.

You’re job and you are like peas and carrots, they just fit so well together. Sure you may have your days where you would rather be at the beach, but your job, colleagues, and work environment offer you enough to genuine connection, security, and opportunities for growth that you are happy with where you are at. Remember, there is no ceiling on your happiness, so continue to challenge yourself, build new connections, and contribute in your own way.
Job Happiness

Positive thinking typically starts with self-talk or the “inner dialogue” we all have. It is our ability to manage the unpleasant times in life in a productive and more positive way. Grade yourself on the frequency and ability to use positive thinking to counter negative thoughts, feelings, and sometimes flat out misconceptions.

So your inner dialogue isn’t on your side? Positive thinking is not about ignoring the troubling things that happen but reacting to them in a more productive way, seeing the possibilities. Gaining control of your thinking can help alleviate depression, distress, anxiety, and improve your overall quality of life. Try making friends with your inner dialogue and negotiating a new way of seeing the negative.

So how is that half full glass of water in front of you? Your way of thinking has potentially helped you through some challenging times, assisted in helping friends out, and occasionally turned your frown upside down, congratulations. Positive thinking is not about ignoring the troubling things that happen, it is about approaching them in a more productive way, seeing the possibilities versus limitations. Keep up the good work!
Positive Thinking

Do you get your stuff done each done? When grading this factor thing about your personal and professional goals and efforts on a daily, weekly, and monthly basis. Do you get what you need and want done?

Whistle while you work. Well I guess sometimes that doesn’t help everybody. There are many factors that go into productivity including motivation, support, the environment, your ability, and even task difficulty. Examine the factors and see which ones are limiting you. There are many ways to boost productivity, but understand what underlies your challenges is the first step. Most individuals claim “they don’t have the resources”, although it is truly about who is most “resourceful”.

Whistle while you work. Sounds like you really know how to get things done. Being able to produce and contribute is always a good feeling. As you know there are many factors that go into productivity including motivation, environment, ability, and task difficulty. Since you already have a productive background, take it a step further and explore what environments are most productive for you. Learn what factors keep you producing and contributing like you do.
Productivity Level
